**Route Description**

Route Overview  
Starting elevation/location: 11,600ft, 39.1991, \-106.1510  
Horseshoe Peak summit elevation/location: 13,918ft, 39.1858, \-106.1851  
Roundtrip distance and elevation gain/loss: 6.0mi 2,350ft

[14ers.com description](https://www.14ers.com/route.php?route=201306020700583):  
While driving up the Fourmile Creek road, locate a 4wd road on the left, near 11,600' and approx. 0.75 mile past the Leavick site. Park here or continue up the road if it's dry. Either way, continue 0.5 mile up this road to a point where it takes a sharp left. Continue left on the road or take a more direct line southwest and you'll get your first view of Horseshoe, near 12,100'.

Follow the road west to approx. 12,300' until you can see the small lakes just east of Horseshoe. You'll also have a nice, head-one view of Boudoir Couloir. Leave the road and traverse southwest toward Boudoir and the large, horseshoe-shaped cirque. Continue your southwest traverse above the lakes, ascend a large rock heap and walk over to the base of Boudoir.

Near 12,900', begin climbing the couloir. As you ascend, you may notice the pitch isn't as steep as it appears during the approach but a fall here could still send you to the bottom. As you approach the top, the angle increases but the route is obvious. Near 13,800', the difficulty quickly eases just a short distance from the summit ridge. Gain the ridge, pass a small building and walk 0.1 mile over to the summit.

Descent: Continue over the summit to follow the Horseshoe Peak east slopes back down to the parking area.

![][image2]

[NOAA: 7 Miles SE Leadville CO  39.19°N 106.2°W (Elev. 12598 ft)](https://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=39.18578955918199&lon=-106.1850959496729&site=all&smap=1)  
![][image3]

* Couloir base is close to the predicted freezing level overnight, will need to assess conditions in the field  
* Slight chance of snow expected in the 24hrs preceding the climb but not enough to create avy concern  
* Partly cloudy then clear Fri PM into Sat AM

CAIC forecast for Tues., 4/23: 

* Low (1) at all elevations  
* Problem(s): Loose wet NW-NE near and above treeline, also E\&W above treeline  
* You can expect generally safe avalanche conditions if you start and end your day early. As the day warms, you can trigger small wet avalanches in the surface snow on slopes steeper than about 40 degrees. Call it a day when the surface snow gets wet and gloppy.  
* Cold snow can still be found on northerly and easterly-facing slopes in the alpine. Be careful below ridgelines and in steep couloir entrances where you see signs of recent wind drifting.

**Objective Hazards**

* Wet avalanches (be on the lookout for pinwheels, roller balls and sinking up to ankles or more in soft snow)  
* Rock fall

**Contingencies & Alternatives**

* Horseshoe Peak can be climbed via its east slopes if Boudoir Couloir conditions are unfavorable
